{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500907"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:19:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:19:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1695"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1695"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.02,0.27,0.54,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55462"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1695"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40998"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42370"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55462"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of acute onset, left-sided chest pain, crushing in nature and radiating to the left jaw. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears alert but uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sublingual glyceryl trinitrate","Send troponin","300 mg aspirin","Perform an electrocardiogram","Subcutaneous morphine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhile all of the above will almost certainly be performed in the setting of acute coronary syndrome (ACS), the most urgent initial step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eperform an electrocardiogram \u003C/strong\u003E. This should be performed within 10 minutes of assessing a patient with suspected ACS to facilitate prompt identification of ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) and the subsequent activation of time-sensitive local reperfusion protocols. This may involve urgent percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI), fibrinolytic therapy, or both, depending on the timing of symptom onset and medical contact, and the availability of PCI facilities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESending troponin levels \u003C/strong\u003Eis also important in the management of ACS, particularly for risk stratification in the absence of ST-elevation. However, it is not as urgent as performing an ECG, which can immediately identify STEMI and the need for timely reperfusion therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, multiple pharmacotherapies are important in the early emergency management of ACS but are not as time-critical. \u003Cstrong\u003ESublingual glyceryl trinitrate\u003C/strong\u003E (GTN) should be administered to symptomatic patients if ACS is suspected, as its vasodilatory effects improve myocardial perfusion. Contraindications include suspected right ventricular infarction or if the patient has recently taken a phosphodiesterase-5 inhibitor, as GTN may precipitate severe hypotension in these cases. A loading dose of\u003Cstrong\u003E aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E(300 mg\u003C/strong\u003E) should be given to patients with suspected ACS as soon as possible after presentation. Aspirin inhibits platelet activation and has been found to reduce the risk of serious vascular events. \u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous morphine\u003C/strong\u003E or other intravenous opioids are recommended for analgesia for pain that is non-responsive to GTN.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An ECG should be performed within 10 minutes of assessing a patient with suspected acute coronary syndrome."],"references":["Thomsett R, Cullen L. Chest pain in primary care. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2018;47:246-51. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/may/chest-pain-in-primary-care","Chew DP, Scott IA, Cullen L, French JK, Briffa TG, Tideman PA, et al. NHFA/CSANZ ACS Guideline 2016 Executive Working Group. National Heart Foundation of Australia \u0026 Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Management of Acute Coronary Syndromes 2016. Heart Lung Circ. 2016;25(9):895-951. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.hlc.2016.06.789"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40998"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1695"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40998"},"att